page.title: 16Ecology: Animals (3)
page.content: Rabbits, common rats, woodmice, field and bank voles are plentiful. Hares, moles, bats, stoats and weasels are regularly seen. Although foxes breed in the area they are more often heard than seen. Their deprivations make poultry keeping an uncertain pastime. They are more likely to be found in Swaffham Poor's Fen and along the Swaffham Lode. Occasional sightings are made of hedgehogs, roe deer, and possibly muntjac. Otters and badgers do not occur. Myxamatosis in the rabbit population is still common, but sufficient numbers are now viable to justify the attentions of a rabbit clearance group.
